<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="s_gauss_int" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Gaussian integers</title>

    <objectives>
        <ol>
            <li>
                <p>
                    Define the Gaussian integers and relate complex norm to number theoretic questions. 
                </p>
            </li>
        </ol>
    </objectives>
    <p>
        We will define the Gaussian integers as the subset of <m>\C</m> consisting of complex numbers whose real and imaginary components are integers. This set is an example of a more general construction called a <em>subring</em> of <m>\C</m>. 
</p>

    
<definition xml:id="d_gauss_int">
<title>Gaussian integers</title>
<statement>
<p>
The <term>Gaussian integers</term> is the subset <m>\Z[i]</m> of <m>\C</m> defined as 
<md number="yes">
    <mrow>\Z[i] \amp = \{a+ib\in \C\mid a,b\in \Z\} </mrow>
</md>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>


<p>
    One particularly useful property of the Gaussian integers is that they are closed under complex addition, subtraction, and multiplication. This means that <m>\Z[i]</m> can be considered as a number system (or ring) of its own. Furthermore, since the complex operations can be viewed as extensions of the corresponding real operations, the addition and multiplication operations of <m>\Z[i]</m> can be viewed as extensions of integer addition and multiplication. In this regard, the Gaussian integers are an example of a more general construction called a <em>subring</em> of <m>\C</m>.
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_subring_C">
<title>Subring of <m>\C</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
A <term>subring</term> of <m>\C</m> is a subset <m>R\subseteq \C</m> containing <m>0</m> and <m>1</m> that satisfies the following properties. 
<ol marker="(i)">
    <li>
        <title>Closed under addition/subtraction</title>
        <p>
            If <m>\alpha,\beta\in R</m>, then <m>\alpha+\beta\in R</m> and <m>\alpha-\beta\in R</m>.
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <title>Closed under multiplication</title>
        <p>
            If <m>\alpha, \beta\in R</m>, then <m>\alpha\beta\in R</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<proposition xml:id="prop_gauss_int">
    <title><m>\Z[i]</m> is a subring</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
          The Gaussian integers form a subring of <m>\C</m>. 
        </p>
    </statement>
</proposition>

<p>
   In studying the arithmetic of <m>\Z[i]</m>, it turns out that the modulus function <m>\abs{a+bi}=\sqrt{a^2+b^2}</m> is an invaluable tool. In the current context, it is more convenient to work with <m>\abs{a+bi}^2=a^2+b^2</m>, since this is an integer. Accordingly, we give this slight variation of the modulus function a special name. 
</p>
<definition xml:id="d_gaussian_norm">
<title>Gaussian norm</title>
<statement>
<p>
The <term>norm function</term> on <m>\Z[i]</m> is the function <m>N\colon \Z[i]\rightarrow \Z_{\geq 0}</m> defined as <m>N(\alpha)=\abs{\alpha}^2</m>. Equivalently, if <m>\alpha=a+ib</m>, we have 
<md number="yes">
    <mrow>N(\alpha) \amp = \alpha\cdot \overline{\alpha}=a^2+b^2</mrow>
</md>.
</p>
</statement>
</definition>

<definition xml:id="d_gauss_int_units">
<title>Units of subrings</title>
<notation>
    <usage><m>R^*</m></usage>
  <description>units of the subring <m>R</m> of <m>\C</m></description>
</notation>
<statement>
<p>
Let <m>R</m> be a subring of <m>\C</m>.  An element <m>\alpha\in R</m> is a <term>unit</term> (or is <term>invertible</term>) if there exists a <m>\beta\in R</m> satisfying <m>\alpha\beta=1</m>. We denote by <m>R^*</m> the set of all units in <m>R</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<remark xml:id="rem_units">
    <title>Units in <m>R</m></title>
    <p>
        It is crucial to understand that the notion of invertibility in <m>R</m> is <em>relative</em> to the subring <m>R</m> in question. Consider the element <m>\alpha=1+i\in (\Z[i])^*</m>, for example. Like any nonzero element of <m>\C</m>, it has a multiplicative inverse <m>\alpha^{-1}</m> satisfying <m>\alpha\alpha^{-1}=1</m>. However, we have 
        <md>
            \alpha^{-1}=\frac{1}{2}-\frac{1}{2}i\not\in \Z[i]
        </md>.
        But is it possible that there is some <em>other</em> element <m>\beta\in \Z[i]</m> satisfying <m>\alpha\beta=1</m>? No! This is a consequence of the fact that inverses in <m>\C</m> are unique: <m>\alpha\alpha^{-1}=\alpha\beta=1</m> implies <m>\alpha^{-1}=\beta</m>. Thus <m>\alpha^{-1}</m> not being an element of <m>\Z[i]</m> is sufficient to conclude that <m>\alpha</m> has no inverse in the subring <m>\Z[i]</m>, and thus that <m>\alpha\notin (\Z[i])^*</m>.
    </p>
</remark>
<p>
    As a first example of the utility of the norm function, we give an elegant proof of the fact that 
    <md>
        (\Z[i])^*=\{1,-1,i,-i\}
    </md>.
</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop_units_gauss_int">
    <title>Units of <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
    
    <statement>
        <p>
           We have 
           <md number="yes">
            <mrow>(Z[i])^* \amp =\{\alpha\in \Z[i]\mid N(\alpha)=1\}=\{1,-1,i,-i\}</mrow>
           </md>.
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            To prove the first set equality, we must show that <m>\alpha</m> is a unit if and only if <m>N(\alpha)=1</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            First assume <m>\alpha\in \Z[i]</m>. By definition, there is an element <m>\beta\in \Z[i]</m> such that <m>\alpha\beta=1</m>. Applying <m>N</m> to both sides of this equation, we see that <m>N(\alpha)N(\beta)=N(1)=1</m>. Since <m>N(\alpha)</m> and <m>N(\beta)</m> are integers, we conclude that <m>N(\alpha)\mid 1</m> in <m>\Z</m>, and hence that <m>N(\alpha)=\pm 1</m>. Since <m>N(\alpha)\geq 0</m>, we conclude that <m>N(\alpha)=1</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
           Now assume <m>N(\alpha)=1</m>. By definition this means <m>\alpha\overline{\alpha}=1</m>. Since <m>\overline{\alpha}\in \Z[i]</m>, we conclude that <m>\alpha\in (\Z[i])^*</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            We now know that <m>\alpha=a+bi\in (\Z[i])^*</m> if and only if <m>N(\alpha)=a^2+b^2=1</m>. Since <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> are integers, it is easy to see that we must have 
            <m>(a,b)\in \{(\pm 1,0),(0,\pm 1)\}</m>, and hence that 
            <m>(\Z[i])^*=\{1,-1,i,-i\}</m>, as claimed. 
        </p>
    </proof>
</proposition>
<p>
    The modulus function will also be useful in our analysis of the question of which integers can be expressed as a sum of squares. 
</p>
<proposition xml:id="prop_sum_of_squares">
    <title>Sum of squares</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>n</m> be a positive integer. The following statements are equivalent. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>n=a^2+b^2</m> for some integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>n</m> factors as <m>\alpha\overline{\alpha}</m> for some <m>\alpha\in \Z[i]</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>n=N(\alpha)</m> for some <m>\alpha\in \Z[i]</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
</proposition>
<corollary xml:id="cor_sum_of_squares">
    <title>Products of sums of squares</title>
    <statement>
        <p>
            If <m>m</m> and <m>n</m> are integers that can be written as a sum of two squares of integers, then <m>mn</m> can be written as a sum of two squares of integers. 
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Assume <m>m=a^2+b^2</m> and <m>n=c^2+d^2</m>. Letting <m>\alpha=a+bi</m> and <m>\beta=c+di</m>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>m \amp =N(\alpha) \amp n=N(\beta)</mrow>
            </md>
            and hence 
            <md>
                <mrow>mn \amp =N(\alpha)N(\beta)=N(\alpha\beta)</mrow>
            </md>.
            It follows from <xref ref="prop_sum_of_squares"/> that <m>mn</m> is a sum of squares. In fact, writing 
            <md>
                \alpha\beta=(ac-bd)+(ad+bc)i
            </md>,
            we see that 
            <md>
                mn=(ac-bd)^2+(ad+bc)^2
            </md>.
        </p>
    </proof>
</corollary>
<definition xml:id="d_divisibility">
<title>Divisibility in subrings</title>
<statement>
<p>
    Let <m>R</m> be a subring of <m>\C</m>. Given <m>\alpha,\beta\in R</m>, we say that <m>\alpha</m> <term>divides</term> <m>\beta</m> in <m>R</m>, denoted <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m>, if there exists a <m>\gamma\in R</m> such that <m>\beta=\alpha\gamma</m>. We write <m>\alpha\nmid \beta</m> if <m>\alpha</m> does not divide <m>\beta</m>. 
</p>
<p>
    We say that <m>\alpha</m> is an <term>associate</term> of <m>\beta</m> if <m>\alpha=u \beta</m> for some unit <m>u\in R^*</m>. 
</p>
</statement>
</definition>
<example xml:id="eg_divisibility">
<title>Divisibility in <m>\Z[i]</m></title>
<statement>
<p>
For the given <m>\alpha, \beta\in \Z[i]</m> determine whether <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m> and whether <m>\beta\mid \alpha</m>.
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=1+2i</m>, <m>\beta=3+i</m>
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            <m>\alpha=1+2i</m>, <m>\beta=2-i</m>
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</statement>
<solution>
<p>
One way of answering this type of question is to use some logic similar to <xref ref="rem_units"/>, zooming out a bit to the larger number system <m>\C</m>. In general, for nonzero elements <m>\alpha, \beta\in \C</m>, we have <m>\beta=\gamma \alpha</m> for if and only if <m>\gamma=\alpha^{-1}\beta</m>. Thus we have <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m> in a subring <m>R</m> if and only if <m>\alpha^{-1}\beta\in R</m>. 
</p>
<p>
Working in <m>\Z[i]</m>, we can also use the norm function to give a <em>necessary</em> (though not necessarily sufficient condition) for divisibility: namely, if <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m>, then we have <m>\beta=\alpha\gamma</m> for some <m>\gamma\in \Z[i]</m>, in which case <m>N(\beta)=N(\alpha)N(\gamma)</m> and <m>N(\alpha)\mid N(\beta)</m>. 
</p>
<p>
    We illustrate both techniques in the two examples. 
<ol>
    <li>
        <p>
            Since <m>N(\alpha)=5</m> and <m>N(\beta)=10</m>, we see that <m>\beta\nmid \alpha</m>, but possibly <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m>. To decide the latter question, we compute 
            <md>
                \alpha^{-1}\beta=(1/5-(2/5)i)(3+i)=1-i\in \Z[i]
            </md>.
            Thus <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
    <li>
        <p>
            In this case we have <m>N(\alpha)=N(\beta)=5</m>. Some arithmetic similar to the above shows that <m>\alpha=-i\beta</m> and <m>\beta=-i\alpha</m>. We conclude that <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m> and <m>\beta\mid \alpha</m>. 
        </p>
    </li>
</ol>
</p>
</solution>
</example>

<proposition xml:id="prop_associates">
    <statement>
        <p>
            Let <m>\alpha</m> and <m>\beta</m> be nonzero elements of <m>R</m>. The following statements are equivalent. 
            <ol>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\alpha</m> is associate to <m>\beta</m>.
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\beta</m> is associate to <m>\alpha</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li>
                    <p>
                        <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m> and <m>\beta\mid \alpha</m> in <m>R</m>. 
                    </p>
                </li>
            </ol>
        </p>
    </statement>
    <proof>
        <p>
            Implication: (i) implies (ii). If <m>\alpha</m> is associate to <m>\beta</m>, then there is a unit <m>u\in R^*</m> such that <m>\alpha=u \beta</m>. Since <m>u\in R^*</m>, we have <m>u^{-1}\in R^*</m> and <m>\beta=u^{-1}\alpha</m>. Thus <m>\beta</m> is associate to <m>\alpha</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Implication: (ii) implies (i). If <m>\beta</m> is associate to <m>\alpha</m>, we have <m>\beta=u \alpha</m> with <m>u\in R^*</m>. In particular, this means <m>\alpha\mid \beta</m>. Since <m>u\in R^*</m>, there is an element <m>u^{-1}\in R</m> such that <m>uu^{-1}=1</m>. It follows that <m>\alpha=u^{-1}\beta</m> and <m>\beta\mid \alpha</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
            Implication: (iii) implies (i). If <m>\alpha \mid \beta</m> and <m>\beta\mid \alpha</m>, we have 
            <md>
                <mrow>\beta \amp = \gamma \alpha</mrow>
                <mrow>\alpha \amp = \delta \beta</mrow>
            </md>
            for some elements <m>\gamma, \delta\in R</m>. But then we have 
            <md>
                \alpha=\delta \beta=(\delta\gamma) \alpha
            </md>.
            Since <m>\alpha</m> is nonzero, it has an inverse <m>\alha^{-1}\in \C</m> (not necessarily an element of <m>R</m>), that allows us to multiplicatively cancel <m>\alpha</m> to obtain <m>1=\delta\gamma</m>. It follows that <m>\delta\in R^*</m> and <m>\gamma\in R^*</m>, and hence that <m>\alpha</m> is a associate to <m>\beta</m>.
        </p>
    </proof>
</proposition>

<definition xml:id="d_prime_irreducible">
<title>Prime and irreducible</title>
<statement>
<p>

</p>
</statement>
</definition>


</section>